================================================================
Lakebase auth: use generate_database_credential (fixes JWT error)
================================================================

Reported issue
--------------
With ``REGISTRY_BACKEND=lakebase`` and PG* set locally, every
connection was rejected by Lakebase with
``Provided authentication token is not a valid JWT encoding``.

Root cause
----------
``LakebaseAuth.password()`` was returning the raw workspace bearer
token from ``WorkspaceClient().config.authenticate()``. Lakebase
requires a **Lakebase-scoped JWT** minted via
``WorkspaceClient.database.generate_database_credential(
instance_names=[<name>])`` — the plain workspace token is not a
JWT and is rejected.

Fixes
-----
1. src/back/core/databricks/LakebaseAuth.py
   - ``password()`` now calls ``generate_database_credential``
     scoped to the bound instance and returns ``cred.token``.
   - New ``instance_name`` property resolves the Lakebase
     instance name from (in order):
       a. ``DATABASE_INSTANCE_NAME`` env var,
       b. ``PGAPPNAME`` env var,
       c. SDK lookup matching ``PGHOST`` against
          ``read_write_dns`` / ``read_only_dns`` (cached for the
          process lifetime).
   - Workspace-client construction extracted into a private
     ``_ensure_workspace`` helper so both the lookup and the
     credential mint share the lazy import.
2. src/shared/config/settings.py
   - Added ``extra="ignore"`` to the Pydantic Settings config so
     the ``.env`` file can carry the ``PG*`` /
     ``DATABASE_INSTANCE_NAME`` entries that ``LakebaseAuth``
     reads directly via ``os.environ`` without raising
     ``extra_forbidden`` validation errors.
3. src/back/objects/domain/SettingsService.py
   - Added ``_enum_short`` and ``_pg_version_short`` helpers and
     used them in ``_lakebase_instance_metadata`` so the admin UI
     shows ``AVAILABLE`` / ``CU_1`` / ``16`` instead of the SDK
     enum reprs ``DatabaseInstanceState.AVAILABLE`` /
     ``DatabaseInstanceCapacity.CU_1`` / ``PG_VERSION_16``.
4. .env.example
   - Documented the local-dev PG* values and the optional
     ``DATABASE_INSTANCE_NAME`` pin.
5. databricks.yml
   - Default ``lakebase_instance`` updated to ``ontobricks-app``
     (matching the canonical instance name used by the new local
     dev setup; deploys still default to the same instance).

Operational note
----------------
Lakebase instance ``ontobricks-app`` (CU_1, PG 16) was provisioned
in the FE VM workspace; database ``ontobricks_registry`` was
created inside it via ``CREATE DATABASE ontobricks_registry``
using a JWT minted via the same SDK call.

